why people are upset. What this story doesn't say is if the opportunity for members of other religions to pay for their own space in similar proximity has been made available-- if yes, then everything is fair. If no, then it isn't. &#10;What I can't get over is that if my parents found out I &quot;wasn't returning to classes&quot; for any reason, including religious worship, *I* would have been the one in trouble, not the school. The whole reason behind this accommodation is that the students weren't coming back from prayer-- what happens when they are finished their education and get employment-- what employer is going to say, &quot;Gee, my employers are taking off for their personal reasons and then not showing up back to work again... I guess instead of reprimanding and/or firing them, I'll give them preferential treatment?&quot; What is this teaching kids about reality and responsibility? "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1175" language="en" documentId="1256" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Cogita" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1256" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="130"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="131" end="525"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="526" end="1175"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>